Youâ€™re on the right trackâ€”and yes, itâ€™s entirely possible to separate your **Explorer** sidebar into two distinct sections in Quartz: one for folders (`Explorer`) and one for tags like `AI`, `CSV`, `Deployment`, etc., under a new section such as **Frequent Tags**.

Hereâ€™s how to do it in `quartz.layout.ts`:

---

### âœ… Step-by-Step Solution: Two Sidebar Sections

#### 1. **Define a new component for â€œFrequent Tagsâ€**

Add this **after** the existing `Component.Explorer()` in your `left` section:

```ts
Component.Explorer({
  title: "Frequent Tags",
  sortFn: (a, b) => a.displayName.localeCompare(b.displayName),
  filterFn: (node) => {
    // Show only non-folder nodes that are tagged and not within folders
    if (!node.isFolder && node.data?.tags?.length > 0) {
      const frequent = new Set([
        "AI", "Data Science", "Automation", "Deployment", "Pandas",
        "API", "Financial Analysis", "SEO", "NLP", "Debugging",
        "Documentation", "Teaching", "Job Search", "Cooking"
      ])
      return node.data.tags.some(tag => frequent.has(tag))
    }
    return false
  },
  mapFn: (node) => {
    node.displayName = `ğŸ·ï¸ ${node.displayName}`
  },
  order: ["filter", "map", "sort"],
})
```

You can expand or tweak the `frequent` tag set freely.

---

#### 2. **Make your existing Explorer only show folders**

This is optional but keeps it cleaner:

```ts
Component.Explorer({
  title: "Explorer",
  folderClickBehavior: "collapse",
  folderDefaultState: "collapsed",
  useSavedState: true,
  filterFn: (node) => node.isFolder,
})
```

---

### ğŸ§ª Bonus: Externalize Filters

If your layout file gets too crowded, extract these into reusable constants:

```ts
// quartz/layout.ts

const frequentTagSet = new Set([
  "AI", "Data Science", "Automation", "Deployment", "Pandas",
  "API", "Financial Analysis", "SEO", "NLP", "Debugging",
  "Documentation", "Teaching", "Job Search", "Cooking"
])

export const tagFilterFn: Options["filterFn"] = (node) => {
  return !node.isFolder && node.data?.tags?.some(tag => frequentTagSet.has(tag))
}

export const tagMapFn: Options["mapFn"] = (node) => {
  node.displayName = `ğŸ·ï¸ ${node.displayName}`
}
```

Then in your layout:

```ts
Component.Explorer({
  title: "Frequent Tags",
  filterFn: tagFilterFn,
  mapFn: tagMapFn,
})
```

---

Would you like help making these `Frequent Tags` into clickable tag pages, or want to group them under their tag headings too (like a nested tag explorer)?

Right â€” `npx quartz check` doesnâ€™t exist. That was incorrect for Quartz v4+. The Quartz repo doesnâ€™t currently include a dedicated CLI command to validate internal links. So you'll need to debug this manually or use a custom script to simulate a â€œcheckâ€ command.

Letâ€™s go deeper into **what you *can* do** to resolve the issue and verify link integrity.

---

## âœ… 1. **Use `quartz build` + `serve` to simulate production**

This is the closest way to test broken links *locally*:

```bash
npx quartz build
npx serve public
```

Then visit [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) and try to follow all internal links.

---

## ğŸ” 2. **Common path issues to audit**

Hereâ€™s a quick diagnostic table:

| Problem | Cause | Fix |
|--------|-------|-----|
| Link works locally but 404s when deployed | Local dev server resolves Obsidian-style `[[My Note]]` but static HTML route becomes `/my-note/` or `/my-note.html` | Use lowercase, hyphenated filenames |
| Links missing `.html` | Quartz doesnâ€™t append extensions | Always use `[[slug]]` and ensure `slug.ts` converts consistently |
| Deployed to subfolder (e.g. GitHub Pages) but links assume root | Relative paths not adjusted | Set `site.baseUrl` correctly in `quartz.config.ts` |
| Mixed casing in filenames | Static sites are case-sensitive | Rename all content files to lowercase |

---

## ğŸ›  3. **Manual path validation script (Node)**

You can run this in your `quartz` directory to check all links:

```ts
// tools/checkInternalLinks.ts
import fs from "fs";
import path from "path";

const contentDir = path.join(process.cwd(), "content");

function extractLinks(markdown: string): string[] {
  const wikiLinks = [...markdown.matchAll(/\[\[([^\]]+)\]\]/g)].map(m => m[1]);
  const mdLinks = [...markdown.matchAll(/\[.*?\]\((.*?)\)/g)].map(m => m[1]);
  return [...wikiLinks, ...mdLinks].filter(link => !link.startsWith("http"));
}

function slugify(filename: string) {
  return filename.toLowerCase().replace(/\s+/g, "-").replace(/\.md$/, "");
}

const allFiles = fs.readdirSync(contentDir);
const slugs = new Set(allFiles.map(f => slugify(f)));

for (const file of allFiles) {
  const fullPath = path.join(contentDir, file);
  const text = fs.readFileSync(fullPath, "utf-8");
  const links = extractLinks(text);
  for (const link of links) {
    const slug = slugify(link);
    if (!slugs.has(slug)) {
      console.warn(`âŒ Broken link in ${file}: ${link} â†’ slugified: ${slug}`);
    }
  }
}
```

Run it like:

```bash
npx ts-node tools/checkInternalLinks.ts
```

Let me know if you'd like a Python version instead.

---

## ğŸ“¦ 4. **If you're using GitHub Pages**

You may need to:

- Add `.nojekyll` to the root of `public/` to avoid GitHubâ€™s Jekyll processing.
- Set the `baseUrl` in `quartz.config.ts`:
  ```ts
  site: {
    baseUrl: "/your-repo-name", // important!
    ...
  }
  ```

---

Would you like help adapting your filenames, resolving specific broken links, or adding a GitHub Pages fix step? You could also share a broken example so we can reverse-engineer the route generation.

That error â€” `EISDIR: illegal operation on a directory, read` â€” means the script tried to `readFileSync` on a directory instead of a file. It happens because `fs.readdirSync` lists *everything* in `content/`, including subdirectories like `content/images/` or nested folders used for routing.

Letâ€™s fix the script so it skips directories and only processes `.md` files.

---

### âœ… **Revised `tools/checkInternalLinks.ts`**

```ts
import fs from "fs";
import path from "path";

// === Configuration ===
const contentDir = path.join(process.cwd(), "content");

function extractLinks(markdown: string): string[] {
  const wikiLinks = [...markdown.matchAll(/\[\[([^\]]+)\]\]/g)].map(m => m[1]);
  const mdLinks = [...markdown.matchAll(/\[.*?\]\((.*?)\)/g)].map(m => m[1]);
  return [...wikiLinks, ...mdLinks].filter(link => !link.startsWith("http"));
}

function slugify(filename: string): string {
  return filename.toLowerCase().replace(/\s+/g, "-").replace(/\.md$/, "").replace(/\//g, "");
}

const allFiles = fs.readdirSync(contentDir, { withFileTypes: true });
const validMarkdownFiles = allFiles
  .filter(entry => entry.isFile() && entry.name.endsWith(".md"))
  .map(entry => entry.name);

const slugs = new Set(validMarkdownFiles.map(f => slugify(f)));

for (const file of validMarkdownFiles) {
  const fullPath = path.join(contentDir, file);
  const text = fs.readFileSync(fullPath, "utf-8");
  const links = extractLinks(text);
  for (const link of links) {
    const slug = slugify(link);
    if (!slugs.has(slug)) {
      console.warn(`âŒ Broken link in ${file}: [[${link}]] â†’ slugified: ${slug}`);
    }
  }
}
```

---

### ğŸƒâ€â™‚ï¸ Run it:

```bash
npx ts-node tools/checkInternalLinks.ts
```

This version:

- Skips directories.
- Only checks `.md` files.
- Compares slugified links against actual filenames.
- Warns on broken internal references (e.g., `[[Note That Doesn't Exist]]`).

---

### ğŸ§  Further improvements you could make

- Add mapping for **aliases** (e.g., a YAML frontmatter field like `aliases: [other-name]`).
- Resolve **subfolders**, if you store Markdown in folders like `content/posts/`.
- Include **GitHub links** to edit broken references (if building contributor workflows).

